      "host": "japannewsheadlines.com",
      "text": "Home National Power failure halts JR Utsunomiya Line trains, prompting passengers to get off and walk Power failure halts JR Utsunomiya Line trains, prompting passengers to get off and walk By admin National 0 Comments They later exited the trains and walked along the tracks to the nearest station. According to the local fire department, several people reported feeling ill and were sent to a hospital.\nThe Utsunomiya Line had stopped operations between Ueno and Utsunomiya stations and resumed services on Monday night, running fewer trains than usual. About 80,000 passengers were affected. The railway plans to resume normal operations Wednesday morning. \nAccording to East Japan Railway Co., an insulator holding an electric wire above the tracks somehow broke and caused an electric leak, damaging signals and other equipment. Mount Fuji, Japan‚Äôs highest peak, has been capped with snow for the first time this season. (NHK) Power transmission trouble halted three JR Utsunomiya Line trains in Kuki, Saitama Prefecture, on Monday, stranding about 1,900 passengers for about two hours. (Japan Times) Typhoon Lan blazed through Tokyo on Monday morning after making landfall along the central Pacific coastline earlier in the day, leaving seven people dead as it pummeled Honshu with heavy rain and strong winds. (Japan Times) Visiting Tokyo Governor Yuriko Koike on Monday announced a plan to make the Japanese capital free of carbon dioxide emissions during the opening and closing days of the 2020 Tokyo Olympics and Paralympics. (Jiji) An industry group says the sales of Japanese animation, related services, and products topped 2 trillion yen, or about 17.6 billion dollars, for the first time in 2016. (NHK) Up to now, it has been a real hassle making advance reservations for Japan‚Äôs bullet trains from overseas. JR East finally set up an online reservation system a while back, but that was only for trains heading north from Tokyo. (rocketnews24.com) Tokyo‚Äôs Nikkei 225 on Monday posted the longest winning streak in its nearly 70-year history as markets cheered the weekend election victory of Japan‚Äôs pro-business prime minister. (Japan Today) Voter turnout for single-seat constituencies in Sunday‚Äôs election for the House of Representatives, the lower chamber of parliament, is projected at around 53.69 pct, the second-lowest in the post-World War II period, a Jiji Press estimate showed Monday. (Jiji) Fresh off a decisive election victory, Prime Minister Shinzo Abe pledged Monday to tackle what he called Japan‚Äôs two national crises: the military threat from North Korea and an aging and shrinking population. (Japan Today) U.S. President Donald Trump on Monday congratulated Prime Minister Shinzo Abe on his ruling camp‚Äôs big victory in the general election the previous day. (Japan Today) Related Posts",
