      "title": "More niche than Netflix: nine specialist streaming services you should try",
      "country": "IE",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T06:26:17Z",
      "url": "http://www.richardhartley.com/2017/10/more-niche-than-netflix-nine-specialist-streaming-services-you-should-try/",
      "host": "richardhartley.com",
      "text": "Tweet Tomas Alfredson‚Äôs Let the Right One In is among the films available on horror service Shudder. Photograph: Magnolia Home Entertainment/Allstar \nStill subscribing to Netflix ? How mainstream. Niche streaming services ‚Äì especially ones that claim to ‚Äúcurate‚Äù their offering ‚Äì are springing up. Some (such as Brown Sugar , which streams Blaxploitation films and films and TV shows aimed at a black audience) are available only in the US, while others (such as the comedy streaming service Seeso ) are already closing down . Here are just a few of those on offer. Shudder ($4.99 a month; available in the UK, Ireland, the US and Canada) \nLive your life in a permanent state of shock, with as much horror ‚Äì schlocky, classic, comic, international ‚Äì as you can take. Hayu (¬£3.99 a month; UK, Ireland and Australia) \nThis reality-TV streaming service features the Kardashians , obviously, plus every flavour of Real Housewife . More niche programmes include Shahs of Sunset and the cosmetic-surgery-gone-wrong show Botched. Mubi (¬£5.99 a month; UK) \nEvery day, an expert-selected movie is added to this service (think classic, independent, global cinema) and another removed. You have 30 days to watch each title, the idea being that you don‚Äôt get the same paralysis of choice as you do with the all-you-can-watch services, plus your film-watching life is curated by someone who knows more than you do. (Also consider the British Film Institute‚Äôs streaming service, BFI Player .) Yaddo (¬£3.99 a month; worldwide) \nAn all-documentary network that can be viewed anywhere in the world. It is run by Nick Fraser , formerly the head of the BBC‚Äôs Storyville strand. Walter Presents (free; UK) \nWalter Iuzzolino is that insufferable friend who grew up watching Fellini when you were slackjawed in front of Postman Pat. Admittedly, this makes him a good curator of foreign-language TV and films for this streaming service for lovers of subtitles from Channel 4. Section II (pay as you watch; worldwide) \nA small but growing site showcasing lesbian drama from around the world, with films available to rent or buy on the site, plus one original series (so far). It also functions as a library of lesbian and queer female films, with links to where to watch them. Dekkoo ($11.99 a month; worldwide) \nDedicated to showcasing cinema and TV aimed at gay men, Dekkoo has also moved into original programming via the series Feral , which is set in the US bible belt. Crunchyroll (some free content, premium subscriptions from ¬£4.99 a month; worldwide) \nHead here for anime, manga and some (mostly Japanese) live-action films. It is also a community, with some lively forums. Spuul (free with ads or $4.99 a month; worldwide) \nFor all the Bollywood you can take, with thousands of hours of films in Hindi, Punjabi, Tamil and other regional languages. The Netflix-style site makes it easy to find films by category.",
