      "score": 1,
      "title": "Leeds United: Fear factor drove us to defeat Robins says Ronaldo Vieira",
      "country": "GB",
      "crawl_date": "2017-10-24T01:56:12Z",
      "url": "http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/sport/football/leeds-united/leeds-united-fear-factor-drove-us-to-defeat-robins-says-ronaldo-vieira-1-8817975",
      "host": "yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk",
      "text": "Have your say \nRonaldo Vieira won the admiration of Bristol City manager Lee Johnson and admitted the threat of a fourth straight loss had driven Leeds United to one of their most convincing performances of the season in a 3-0 victory at Ashton Gate. \nThe 19-year-old was named in United‚Äôs starting line-up for the first time in a league game this term and contributed heavily to a rejuvenated display which stemmed the flow of defeats suffered by Thomas Christiansen‚Äôs side. Samuel Saiz celebrates scoring the opening goal against Bristol City. \nLeeds had dropped from first place in the Championship to sixth during a run of four losses in five games but climbed back up to fourth yesterday by ending Bristol City‚Äôs 12-match unbeaten run and inflicting their first home defeat. \nChristiansen responded to calls to strengthen his midfield by drafting in Vieira and allowing Kalvin Phillips to assume a more attacking role. Leeds scored twice in the first 15 minutes through a Samuel Saiz brace and sealed their win in the second half with a header from Pierre-Michel Lasogga. \nJohnson credited England Under-20 international Vieira for ‚Äúrunning the show‚Äù and Vieira said: ‚ÄúWe just knew we had to win the game. \n‚ÄúWe couldn‚Äôt go four games in a row losing if we wanted to be up there at the end of the season. All the boys worked hard during the week. Ronaldo Vieira battles in midfield against Bristol City. \n‚ÄúWe had a lot of meetings about Bristol and they‚Äôre a good team but I think we overlooked them and just tried to get the three points.‚Äù \nChristiansen came in for criticism for the first time since his appointment as head coach as an impressive start to the season faded either side of the recent international break but Vieira insisted the term was still in its infancy and said United‚Äôs players had not been suffering from excessive pressure. \n‚ÄúFrom the outside I felt it but from the inside, it‚Äôs still early,‚Äù he said. ‚ÄúIt‚Äôll still be early until after Christmas. \n‚ÄúObviously the fans want to win and if we lose three games there‚Äôs a lot of pressure from the outside but on the inside everyone knew that we‚Äôve got time, we‚Äôre still up there and still had a chance. \n‚ÄúThere were only six points between four teams and you can get that in four days, Saturday to Tuesday. Everyone‚Äôs happy and hopefully we can carry it on.‚Äù \nVieira made a huge impact last season during his first year as a professional with Leeds, earning a maiden England youth cap and a new four-year contract as a result, but a combination of injury and Christiansen‚Äôs selection policy had denied him a start in any of United‚Äôs initial 12 league games. \n‚ÄúI‚Äôm just pleased to be back out there enjoying myself and helping the team as much as I can,‚Äù Vieira said. \n‚ÄúI feel like I took my chance well but I came into the game just thinking ‚ÄòI‚Äôm going to do as much as I can to help the team.‚Äô I thought I did well and we‚Äôll see what happens now.‚Äù Leeds United Nostalgia: Maverick midfielder Batty proved vital man for United Bristol City 0 Leeds United 3: Coach Christiansen dedicates weekend win at City to Dallas Sign in",
