      "host": "henleystandard.co.uk",
      "text": "Proposal for 100 homes is pre-emptive, say councillors \nPLANS for 100 homes near Watlington have been criticised by parish councillors as pre-emptive. \nThe council‚Äôs planning committee has objected to the proposed development on land off Pyrton Lane, in Pyrton parish, by Providence Land. \nMembers said there was no need for houses on the site and that the proposed Watlington bypass could be viable with fewer houses on the land or even none. \nThe applicant had proposed a greater stretch of the ‚Äúedge road‚Äù going through the site than suggested in the draft Watlington neighbourhood plan and it would have an adverse impact on part of Pyrton Lane. \nThe committee also said there were ‚Äútoo many unknowns‚Äù with the development, especially with the proposal by the Government‚Äôs Homes and Communities Agency to build 3,000 new homes on Chalgrove Airfield. \nThe committee added: ‚ÄúThere is no safeguarded area for school buildings and their playing fields to allow extension. \n‚ÄúThere is no safeguarded area for sport and recreation land. This application is tantamount to coalescence between Watlington and Pyrton. \n‚ÄúThe number of houses on this site would impact on Watlington over and above those allocated to the town in the neighbourhood plan.‚Äù \nSouth Oxfordshire District Council, the planning authority, will make the final decision. 23 October 2017",
